
===================================
📌 1. Finglish Version (Persian Latin Script)
===================================

📖 **Tashrih:**
    Dastoor `editres` yek barname baraye tagheer daadan resource-ha (manabe) barname-haye X Toolkit hast. Ba estefade az `editres`, shoma mitavanid resource-haye yek barname-ye fa'al ra be soorat dynamic tagheer dahid, bedoone inke niaz bashad barname ra dobare compile konid. In barname bishtar baraye debug kardane UI estefade mishavad.

⚙️ **Gozine-ha:**
    🔹 `-id windowID`  --> 🆔  WindowID barnameyi ke mikhahid resource-hayash ra tagheer dahid ra moshakhas mikonad.
    🔹 `-tree`     --> 🌳 Namayesh derakhti az widget-ha (ajza) barname ra neshan midahad.
    🔹 `-help`     --> ❓ Rahnamayi estefade az dastoor ra neshan midahad.

🛠 **Mesal-ha:**

    $ editres -id 0x2a0000b

    🔹 In dastoor barnameyi ba ID `0x2a0000b` ra baz mikonad va shoma mitavanid resource-hayash ra az tarigh GUI tagheer dahid.

    $ editres -tree

    🔹 In dastoor yek derakht az widget-ha ra dar terminal neshan midahad ke structure UI ra baraye debug kardan asan mikonad.

✅ **Mesal sade:**

    $ editres
    
    🔹 Agar be tartibi ke daraye environment variabel `DISPLAY` bashid va yek barnameye X Toolkit dar hale ejra bashad, ba ejraye sade `editres`, barname baraye shoma baz mishavad ta resource hayash ra tagheer dahid. Agar `DISPLAY` set nashode bashad, shoma bayad az gozine `-id` estefade konid.

===================================
📌 2. English Version
===================================

📖 **Description:**
    The `editres` command is a program for dynamically editing the resources of X Toolkit applications. With `editres`, you can change an application's resources without recompiling it. It's mostly used for UI debugging.

⚙️ **Options:**
    🔹 `-id windowID`  --> 🆔 Specifies the window ID of the application you want to edit the resources of.
    🔹 `-tree`     --> 🌳 Shows a tree representation of the application's widgets.
    🔹 `-help`     --> ❓ Displays the command's help message.

🛠 **Examples:**

    $ editres -id 0x2a0000b

    🔹 This command opens the application with ID `0x2a0000b`, allowing you to edit its resources through a GUI.

    $ editres -tree

    🔹 This command displays a widget tree in the terminal, making it easier to debug the UI structure.

✅ **Simple Example:**

    $ editres

    🔹 If your `DISPLAY` environment variable is set and an X Toolkit application is running, simply running `editres` will open the program for resource editing. If `DISPLAY` is not set, you need to use the `-id` option.
